<dl id="n05179i"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05179i">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05179i"> 179(i)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> old folks at home <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n05179i"><li>FW 390.10 </li><li><a href="../../flex/nb/lexnb.htm#n05179i">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/nb/l39nb.htm#n05179i">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n05179i">MS BL 47481-17</ms> </li><li>JJA 56.51 <a name="nbd2y" href="../../ff/fdra/nda.htm#nbd2y">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/nb/nbd2.htm#n05179i">Draft: II.4&sect;2.2</a>+</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">I would like to call your attention to the efforts to represent <mark>the old folks&apos; performances</mark> of Welsh music. To name but a few of the points where it fails: the accent, or want of it; the melodic intervals, often not diatonic, and even wavering, not through ignorance or vocal incapacity; the grace notes, or more accurately perhaps explanatory or commentatory notes, often highly elaborate and queerly timed with respect to any possible bars, and certain tricks of utterance, perhaps not unconnected with grace notes. <small> Alfred Perceval Graves, <a name="ILMS" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#ILMS"><cite title="source">Irish Literary and Musical Studies</cite></a>, (1913) [Folk Song] 186</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
